Netherlands:
------------
[Subscribers are referred to the full presentation (20 slides) at the source URL. The following data, from slide No 10, have not been included in earlier postings on SBV in the Netherlands. - Mod.AS]

Sheep farms concerned
- Lambs are mainly born at 135-151 days; normal 147;
- Lambs are sometimes born alive;
- 4 Farms also had a lambing period in November; in all cases without problems;
- Several breeds (Suffolk, Texel, Blue Texel, Dairy, Flevolander, Swifter, Blessumer, cross-breds)
- As well synchronised as non-synchronised sheep

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[The Dutch presentation shows malformed lambs; no malformations in cattle are shown (neither are they shown in the Belgian or the German presentations). On what ground have cattle holdings been reported suspicious and tested for SBV? (eg 84 holdings -- so far -- in the Netherlands, of which 57 already tested and found negative).

According to the official Dutch and Belgian updates, the SBV situation, expressed in lab results as of noon 13 Jan 2012, was the following:

1. Belgium:
Total tested (all species) - 76
Cattle: tested 40, positive 0
sheep: tested 34, positive 23 (67.6 percent)
goats: tested 2, positive 0.
Map at: http://www.afsca.be/_pictures/users/Schmallenberg_20120113_000.jpg

2. Netherlands:
Total number of tested holdings - 138 (all species; out of 212 holdings from which samples have been derived).
cattle: tested 57, positive 0.
sheep: tested 74, positive 55 (74.3 percent)
goats: tested 7, positive 2 (28.6 percent).
Map at: http://www.vwa.nl/txmpub/files/?p_file_id=2201854

The Netherlands and Belgium have already notified to the OIE the introduction of SBV as an emerging disease. The 2 counties commendably publish daily bulletins on the test results and their mapping. -Mod.AS].

