[3]
Date: Thu 12 Jan 2012
Source: EU's DG Health & Consumers, presentations of the Standing Committee on the Food Chain and Animal Health (SCFCAH) meeting in Brussels, 11-12 Jan 2012 [summarised, edited]
http://ec.europa.eu/food/committees/regulatory/scfcah/animal_health/presentations/11120112_schallenberg_germany.pdf

SBV in Germany
--------------
[Subscribers are referred to the full presentation (8 slides) at the source URL. The following data, from slides 6,7,8 are new or have only been partly included in earlier postings on SBV in Germany. - Mod.AS]

Slide 6
- Virus provisionally designated "Schmallenberg virus" (SBV) according to the origin of the 1st positive samples
- 12 PCR-positive cattle in 6 holdings detected between August and December [2011], including one positive stillborn twin calf.[see also item 4 and commentary at bottom].
- Samples from holdings in unaffected regions (southern part of Germany, Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania) are negative
- 09 Jan 2012: First SBV-positive samples from malformed lambs. Up to now, positive lambs from 14 farms (7 in North Rhine-Westphalia and 7 in Lower Saxony). Positive PCR results from brain samples.
- Further cases from malformed lambs are reported and samples are under investigation.

Slide No 7
Ongoing activities in FLI
- further epidemiological examination of cattle and sheep holdings in the affected area
- laboratory testing mainly of brain samples of malformed calves/lambs; the PCR protocol was also transferred to laboratories in the Netherlands, Belgium, UK, Italy, Denmark.
- first inoculation experiment with cattle finished
- virus isolation in cell culture successful. Virus is well growing on BHK-cells.
- development of tools for serological testing of cattle for SBV; indirect IF and neutralisation test have been established.
- Simbu-serogroup reference viruses were obtained from the World Reference Center for ARBO viruses (UTMB, Texas, USA). The viruses are well growing and sequencing for comparison studies has started.

Slide No 8
"news" around the virus since last SCOFCAH
- virus seems to cause intrauterine malformations in sheep (NL/D) and cattle (1 confirmed case up to now)[see comment]
- detection of the virus in samples from sheep in Belgium
- detection of stillbirth and malformations in new born lambs in North Rhine-Westphalia and Lower Saxony; SBV was detected in brain samples from lambs with congenital abnormalities (FLI)
- Small scale serological studies will start as soon as possible
- no indications for the affection of humans by SBV

