[4]
Date: Fri 13 Jan 2012
From: Martin Beer <Martin.Beer@fli.bund.de>


Subject: 'Schmallenberg Virus': Accession numbers for sequence information available
-----------------------------------------------------
Friedrich-Loeffler-Institut (FLI) publishes accession numbers at the Europe Nucleotide Archive.

After the discovery of the novel orthobunyavirus tentatively designated as 'Schmallenberg Virus' in November 2011, the Friedrich-Loeffler-Institut (FLI) confirmed now about 20 cases (6 in cattle, 16 in sheep with analysis of more suspected cases from new areas still pending) in Germany so far [see comment].

The institute already distributes the protocol for genome detection and will provide the virus isolate. The full-length sequences for the segments L, M, and S of the Schmallenberg virus genome will shortly be available from the European Nucleotide Archive (https://www.ebi.ac.uk/ena/) and with a short delay from GenBank and DDBJ under the accessions HE649912, HE649913, and HE649914.

On behalf of the FLI Schmallenberg Virus Study Group

PD Dr. Martin Beer, Director of Institute of Diagnostic Virology;
Prof. Dr. Dr. h.c. Thomas. C. Mettenleiter, President of the FLI

--
Communicated by:
Dr. Martin Beer
Head Institute of Diagnostic Virology
Friedrich-Loeffler-Institut
Am Suedufer 10
17493 Greifswald-Insel Riems
Germany
<Martin.Beer@fli.bund.de>

[In view of the fact that, so far, no SBV-positive results have been reported from the Netherlands and Belgium in cattle progeny (in contrast to sheep), we have asked Dr Beer to kindly provide us with additional details on SBV in German cattle (items 3 and 4 above). We are very grateful for the following information which he has proficiently and immediately provided:

1. The cases in sheep are all from congenitally malformed lambs. The cases in cattle are different. Only one case is a stillborn twin calf. The other 5 cattle cases are farms with PCR positive adult cattle (these are the early cases from autumn 2011) which were sampled due to acute signs of disease (fever, milk drop).

2. The calf was stillborn mid of December 2011, about 10 days before the calculated date of normal birth. As far as I know, the calf was more or less normal. Only the abdomen was a little bit enlarged."

The reason for the absence of positive cases in cattle remains to be clarified. Could it be related to the fact that cattle reacted clinically to the initial infection in Aug-Sep 2011, in Germany and the Netherlands, and the virus did not cross the placental barrier?! Other possible explanations have been suggested as well. A definitive answer is not expected before April-May; in case transplacental infection of foeti took place during early pregnancy, CNS-related changes in cattle progeny may still be encountered. - Mod.AS

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/1zJl.]
